{"title_page": "Cyclone Helen (2008)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Other hurricanes|Tropical Storm Helen}}\n{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Year=2008\n| Name=Tropical Cyclone Helen\n| Basin=Aus\n| Type=Tropical storm \n| Image location=Helen MODIS Aqua 04 jan 2008 0450Z.jpg\n| Image name=Tropical Cyclone Helen over the [[Joseph Bonaparte Gulf]] on 4&nbsp;January\n| Formed=28 December 2007\n| Dissipated= 7 January 2008\n| 1-min winds=45\n| 10-min winds=50\n| Gusts=70\n| Pressure=975\n| Fatalities=1 direct\n| Damages=1.1\n| Inflated=1\n| Areas=[[Far North Queensland]], [[Northern Territory]], and [[Western Australia]]\n| Hurricane season=[[2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season]]\n}}\n\n'''Tropical Cyclone Helen''' was the first [[tropical cyclone]] to bring [[gale]]-force winds to [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin, Australia]] since 1985. The fourth [[tropical cyclone naming|named storm]] of the [[2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season]], Helen developed out of a weak [[low-pressure area|area of low pressure]] in late December over the [[Top End]] region of Australia. Generally tracking westward, the system eventually intensified into a tropical cyclone and was given the name Helen on 2&nbsp;January. By this time, it was situated over the [[Joseph Bonaparte Gulf]] and was beginning to [[Retrograde motion#Within the atmosphere|retrograde]] eastward. Late on 4&nbsp;January, the storm made [[landfall]] near [[Channel Point Coastal Reserve|Channel Point]] with winds of 95&nbsp;km/h (60&nbsp;mph) though rapidly weakened to a tropical low within 12&nbsp;hours. Gradually accelerating, the remnants of Helen moved over the [[Gulf of Carpentaria]] before striking land again on 6&nbsp;January. The system was last noted over the [[Cape York Peninsula]] on 7&nbsp;January.\n\nFrom late December through 6&nbsp;January, Helen and its precursor low produced significant rainfall over the Northern Territory, generally amounting between {{convert|100|and|200|mm|abbr=on}}. One person drowned in the [[Victoria River (Northern Territory)|Victoria River]] after his car was swept away in a flood. As a tropical cyclone, Helen produced significant wind gusts across the Top End, peaking at 120&nbsp;km/h (75&nbsp;mph), downing thousands of trees. In Darwin, roughly 15,000 people were without power due to the storm, more than 100 of which remained so four days after the storm. Overall losses from the storm reached A$1.3&nbsp;million (US$1.1&nbsp;million) with an additional A$1&nbsp;million (US$882,000){{#tag:ref|Monetary values are in 2008 [[Australian dollar|AUD]] and [[United States dollar|USD]]|group=\"nb\"|name=\"Values\"}} in cleanup costs.\n\n==Meteorological history==\n{{storm path|Helen 2007 track.png}}\nAs early as autumn 2007, long-range [[Numerical weather prediction|forecast models]] indicated that a [[La Ni\u00f1a]] would develop by December of that year. In general, this event results in increased [[sea surface temperature]]s near Australia. Following this, a strong [[Madden\u2013Julian oscillation]] phase took shape, leading to the development of [[Tropical Cyclone Melanie (2007)|Tropical Cyclone Melanie]] off the coast of [[Western Australia]] and an [[low-pressure area|area of low pressure]] over the [[Top End]] by 28&nbsp;December. Situated over land, the system initially embedded within a disorganised [[Trough (meteorology)|trough]] and to intensify as it slowly tracked eastward. By 30&nbsp;December, it separated itself from the trough and travelled towards the west. The following day, the interaction between the two systems allowed the low to significantly deepen, attaining a [[barometric pressure]] of 993&nbsp;[[Bar (unit)|mbar]] ([[Pascal (unit)|hPa]]; 29.32&nbsp;[[Inches of Mercury|inHg]]). This strengthening was short-lived as [[wind shear]] over the low increased, displacing [[Atmospheric convection#Concerns regarding severe deep moist convection|convection]] from its centre.<ref name=\"TCR\">{{cite web|work=Darwin Tropical Cyclone Warning Centre|publisher=Australian Bureau of Meteorology|year=2008|accessdate=20 January 2011|title=Tropical Cyclone Helen Tropical Cyclone Report|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/history/pdf/helen.pdf}}</ref>\n\nBy 2&nbsp;January, the weak low moved over the [[Joseph Bonaparte Gulf]] where it slowly developed over the following day.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> Once over water, the [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]] (JTWC) designated the system as Tropical Depression 09S.<ref name=\"JTWCBT\">{{cite web|work=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|publisher=United States Navy|year=2009|accessdate=23 January 2011|title=Tropical Cyclone 09S (Helen) Best Track|url=http://www.usno.navy.mil/NOOC/nmfc-ph/RSS/jtwc/best_tracks/2008/2008s-bsh/bsh102008.txt|format=[[Text file|TXT]]}}</ref> As organisation improved, a mid-level [[subtropical ridge]] over Western Australia pushed the system westward, away from the [[Kimberley (Western Australia)|Kimberley coast]]. Steadily strengthening, the low attained gale-force winds near its centre during the morning of 4&nbsp;January and was subsequently named Helen by the [[Bureau of Meteorology (Australia)|Bureau of Meteorology]]. Shortly thereafter, a strong westerly [[monsoon trough|monsoon flow]] to the north caused Helen to turn eastward, back towards land. Intensification continued up until [[landfall]], by which time Helen had attained Category&nbsp;2 status on the [[Tropical cyclone scales#Australia|Australian tropical cyclone intensity scale]]. [[Maximum sustained wind|Maximum ten-minute sustained wind]]s reached 95&nbsp;km/h (60&nbsp;mph) and the storm's [[barometric pressure]] decreased to 975&nbsp;[[Bar (unit)|mbar]] ([[Pascal (unit)|hPa]]; 28.79&nbsp;[[Inches of Mercury|inHg]]).<ref name=\"TCR\"/> The JTWC assessed Helen to have been slightly weaker, with peak winds estimated at 85&nbsp;km/h (50&nbsp;mph).<ref name=\"JTWCBT\"/>\n\nAround 10:00&nbsp;pm local time on 4&nbsp;January, the centre of Tropical Cyclone Helen made landfall near Channel Point. As it moved ashore, the storm developed an [[Eye (cyclone)|eye]]; however, this feature began breaking apart once overland and the eyewall merged into the system's [[Rainband#Tropical cyclones|feeder bands]]. Roughly 12&nbsp;hours after landfall, Helen weakened to a tropical low before moving over the [[Gulf of Carpentaria]] late on 5&nbsp;January. Due to an increase in forward motion, the system was unable to regenerate sufficient convection to be reclassified a tropical cyclone before making a second landfall along the Cape York Peninsula.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> Once overland again, the remnants of Helen abruptly slowed and were last noted on 7&nbsp;January in the same region.<ref name=\"JTWCBT\"/>\n\n==Preparations==\n[[File:Powerlines down in Alawa following Cyclone Helen.jpg|thumb|right|Trees and power lines downed in Darwin as a result of Cyclone Helen]]\nStarting in late December, widespread rains produced by the precursor to Helen prompted the issuance of flood warnings throughout the Top End region.<ref name=\"TCR\"/><ref name=\"ABC4\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=NT flood warning as low drifts north |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/02/2130427.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxFrYefP?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/02/2130427.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Prior to the arrival of Cyclone Helen on 4&nbsp;January, the Bureau of Meteorology issued [[Tropical cyclone warnings and watches|cyclone warnings]] for areas between the [[Mitchell Plateau]], in Western Australia, to [[Cape Hotham Light|Cape Hotham]] in the Northern Territory. According to local officials, flooding was the greatest concern from the storm rather than wind damage.<ref name=\"ABC1\">{{cite web |author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Top End on alert as cyclone forms |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2131771.htm?site=news |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxC1Rra3?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2131771.htm?site=news |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> The warning area was later condensed to encompass areas from [[Wadeye, Northern Territory|Wadeye]] to Cape Hotham, including Darwin and the [[Tiwi Islands]].<ref name=\"ABC2\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Helen upgraded, shelters open in Darwin |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2132081.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxCeOLkn?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2132081.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> By 6&nbsp;January, warnings were issued for the western coast of the Cape York Peninsula between [[Karumba, Queensland|Karumba]] and [[Weipa, Queensland|Weipa]] as the remnants of Helen were forecast to regain storm intensity.<ref name=\"ABC3\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=6 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Bureau predicts cyclone to hit Cape York |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/06/2132566.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxF5zkc8?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/06/2132566.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn light of Helen's approach in the Top End region, the [[Compass Resources]] mining company suspended construction of a new mine in [[Batchelor, Northern Territory|Batchelor]].<ref name=\"ABC1\"/> Mining at the [[Ranger Uranium Mine]] maintained by [[Energy Resources of Australia]] was also suspended until the storm passed.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rebecca Keenan and Angela Macdonald-Smith|publisher=Bloomberg News|date=4 January 2008|accessdate=23 January 2011|title=Energy Resources Stops Uranium Mining Due to Cyclone (Update2)|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid%3Dnewsarchive%26sid%3DaJc3NJ7_FyIw%26refer%3Daustralia|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxE8LwnD?url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aJc3NJ7_FyIw&refer=australia|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 January 2011}}</ref> The [[George Brown Darwin Botanic Gardens]] and [[Territory Wildlife Park]] were also closed for the duration of the storm.<ref name=\"ABC1\"/> Residents in the [[Aboriginal people#Oceania|Aboriginal community]] of Wadeye were strongly advised to take precautions for the storm.<ref>{{cite web|author=Australian Associated Press |publisher=The North Queensland Register |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone warning for WA and NT |url=http://nqr.farmonline.com.au/news/nationalrural/agribusiness-and-general/general/cyclone-warning-for-wa-and-nt/56915.aspx |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxCRN4xh?url=http://nqr.farmonline.com.au/news/nationalrural/agribusiness-and-general/general/cyclone-warning-for-wa-and-nt/56915.aspx |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Following the issuance of a cyclone warning in Darwin, local shelters were opened to the public.<ref name=\"ABC2\"/> At the [[Darwin International Airport]], all incoming and outgoing flights through [[Jetstar Airways]] were cancelled while [[Tiger Airways]] rescheduled their flights and no changes were made by [[Qantas]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Helen bears down on coast |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2132142.htm?site=news |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxDEDiRO?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2132142.htm?site=news |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Darwin Harbour was mostly shut down as seas became too rough to sail in. Schools and day cares within a {{convert|50|km|mi|abbr=on}} radius of the city were closed on 4&nbsp;January.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tara Ravens |agency=Australian Associated Press |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Helen due to hit NT coast |url=http://news.smh.com.au/national/cyclone-helen-due-to-hit-nt-coast-20080104-1k6n.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxDqDev1?url=http://news.smh.com.au/national/cyclone-helen-due-to-hit-nt-coast-20080104-1k6n.html |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Impact and aftermath==\n[[File:Cyclone Helen 4019.jpg|thumb|left|Power crews clearing trees and fixing downed wires in the wake of Cyclone Helen]]\nThroughout the Top End region, the precursor to Helen resulted in a prolonged period of moderate rains over a relatively large area. These rains caused the Victoria River to swell over its banks and flood nearby areas. On 4&nbsp;January, a car with three people was swept away by the river; two of the passengers managed to escape and swim to shore, but the third person remained trapped. Aerial searches were made later that day for him,<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Air search for missing NT man |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2131735.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxGP5qiG?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2131735.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> though he was later declared dead.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> After becoming a tropical cyclone, the storm produced additional moderate to heavy rainfall, generally totaling between {{convert|100|and|200|mm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> Between 1 and 6&nbsp;January, a total of {{convert|174.6|mm|in|abbr=on}} of rain fell in Darwin.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Australian Bureau of Meteorology|year=2008|accessdate=23 January 2011|title=2008 Daily Rainfall Summary for Stokes Hill, Northern Territory|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/jsp/ncc/cdio/weatherData/av?p_display_type=dailyDataFile&p_stn_num=014167&p_startYear=2008&statType=Rainfall+of+....&p_nccObsCode=136}}</ref> These rains affected two additional major rivers in the area: the [[Adelaide River|Adelaide]] and [[Katherine River|Katherine]] rivers.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> Near where the storm made landfall, wind gusts up to 120&nbsp;km/h (75&nbsp;mph) were recorded; Darwin recorded a maximum wind gust of {{convert|102|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} as Helen moved by the city.<ref name=\"TCR\"/>\n\nNear Channel Point, the cyclone brought a [[storm surge]] of {{convert|2|to|3|m|ft|abbr=on}}, barely surpassing the highest [[astronomical tide]] in a few areas. In some cases, waves over topped [[sand dune]]s but no damage took place. Roughly 10-15% of trees in open areas were snapped or uprooted by high winds. Only two structures sustained direct wind damage while several others were struck by downed trees. Damage was more widespread in Darwin where roughly 15,000 homes, 60% of the city's residences, were left without power. Approximately 1,500 trees were downed in the city, falling on roads, homes and power lines. In the days following the storm's passage, the Adelaide and Katherine rivers continued to rise, of which the former exceeded minor flood levels.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> In the harbour, seven vessels washed ashore, each sustaining minor damage.<ref name=\"ABC6\"/> Losses caused by the storm was placed at A$1.3&nbsp;million (US$1.1&nbsp;million).{{#tag:ref||name=\"Values\"|group=\"nb\"}}<ref name=\"ABC5\">{{cite web|author=Margie Smithurst |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=29 February 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Trees |url=http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/nt/content/2006/s2176883.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxKQJ7Zf?url=http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/nt/content/2006/s2176883.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe day after Helen passed through, cleanup efforts began as power crews had to remove downed trees before fixing power lines.<ref>{{cite web|author=Australian Associated Press |publisher=News.au |date=5 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Helen still a threat |url=http://www.news.com.au/cyclone-helen-still-a-threat/story-e6frfkp9-1111115252958 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxK9HvWf?url=http://www.news.com.au/cyclone-helen-still-a-threat/story-e6frfkp9-1111115252958 |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> The main power lines in the city were restored within 24&nbsp;hours and rural areas were stated to have their power back within a day or two.<ref>{{cite web |author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=6 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Power restored to Darwin homes after cyclone |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/06/2132504.htm?section=australia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxKyPANS?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/06/2132504.htm?section=australia |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Two days after the storm, 500 homes remained without electricity and frustrated residents were further angered after discovering that the Power and Water agency was in control of tree removal and not emergency services. With the power company in charge of clearing downed trees, they stated that their crews would only be dealing with cases involved power lines. Residents with trees in their yards or even on their homes were told to contact private contractors to remove them.<ref name=\"ABC6\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=7 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Power and Water take strong stance over tree-clearing |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/07/2132968.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxLkLJnb?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/07/2132968.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> By 9&nbsp;January, more than 100 homes were still without power in northern Darwin, resulting in angry outcries from those still left in the dark.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ben Langford |newspaper=Northern Territory News |date=9 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Power delay anger |url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2008/01/09/3049_ntnews.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxLHVvnH?url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2008/01/09/3049_ntnews.html |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Cleanup efforts dragged on for more than two months as debris was still present in Darwin in March.<ref name=\"ABC5\"/> Removal of tree stumps took through at least mid-April as the cost to remove downed trees exceeded A$1&nbsp;million (US$882,000).{{#tag:ref||name=\"Values\"|group=\"nb\"}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=18 April 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Helen clean-up bill hits $1m |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/04/18/2221033.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxKnxS8M?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/04/18/2221033.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Due to the damage wrought by Helen, its name was [[Tropical cyclone naming#Retirement|retired]] following its usage. However, it was not replaced by any particular name as a new naming scheme was implemented the following season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/about/names.shtml|publisher=Bureau of Meteorology|year=2010|title=Tropical Cyclone Names}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season]]\n*[[Timeline of the 2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season]]\n*[[1984\u201385 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical_Cyclone_Gretel|Cyclone Gretel]]&nbsp;\u2013 The last storm to bring gale-force winds to [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] prior to Helen\n*[[Cyclone Carlos (2011)|Cyclone Carlos]]&nbsp;\u2013 The next cyclone to hit Darwin, bringing record rainfall to the city.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cyclone Helen}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070421094952/http://www.wmo.int/index-en.html World Meteorological Organization]\n* [http://www.bom.gov.au/weather/cyclone/ Australian Bureau of Meteorology]\n* [http://www.usno.navy.mil/JTWC Joint Typhoon Warning Center]\n\n{{2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season buttons}}\n{{Retired Australian cyclones}}\n{{Category 2 Australian region tropical cyclones}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Helen (2008)}}\n[[Category:2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season|2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season]]\n[[Category:Category 2 Australian region cyclones]]\n[[Category:1990\u201391 Australian region cyclone season]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Other hurricanes|Tropical Storm Helen}}\n{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Year=2008\n| Name=Tropical Cyclone Helen\n| Basin=Aus\n| Type=Tropical storm \n| Image location=Helen MODIS Aqua 04 jan 2008 0450Z.jpg\n| Image name=Tropical Cyclone Helen over the [[Joseph Bonaparte Gulf]] on 4&nbsp;January\n| Formed=28 December 2007\n| Dissipated= 7 January 2008\n| 1-min winds=45\n| 10-min winds=50\n| Gusts=70\n| Pressure=975\n| Fatalities=1 direct\n| Damages=1.1\n| Inflated=1\n| Areas=[[Far North Queensland]], [[Northern Territory]], and [[Western Australia]]\n| Hurricane season=[[2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season]]\n}}\n\n'''Tropical Cyclone Helen''' was the first [[tropical cyclone]] to bring [[gale]]-force winds to [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin, Australia]] since 1985. The fourth [[tropical cyclone naming|named storm]] of the [[2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season]], Helen developed out of a weak [[low-pressure area|area of low pressure]] in late December over the [[Top End]] region of Australia. Generally tracking westward, the system eventually intensified into a tropical cyclone and was given the name Helen on 2&nbsp;January. By this time, it was situated over the [[Joseph Bonaparte Gulf]] and was beginning to [[Retrograde motion#Within the atmosphere|retrograde]] eastward. Late on 4&nbsp;January, the storm made [[landfall]] near [[Channel Point Coastal Reserve|Channel Point]] with winds of 95&nbsp;km/h (60&nbsp;mph) though rapidly weakened to a tropical low within 12&nbsp;hours. Gradually accelerating, the remnants of Helen moved over the [[Gulf of Carpentaria]] before striking land again on 6&nbsp;January. The system was last noted over the [[Cape York Peninsula]] on 7&nbsp;January.\n\nFrom late December through 6&nbsp;January, Helen and its precursor low produced significant rainfall over the Northern Territory, generally amounting between {{convert|100|and|200|mm|abbr=on}}. One person drowned in the [[Victoria River (Northern Territory)|Victoria River]] after his car was swept away in a flood. As a tropical cyclone, Helen produced significant wind gusts across the Top End, peaking at 120&nbsp;km/h (75&nbsp;mph), downing thousands of trees. In Darwin, roughly 15,000 people were without power due to the storm, more than 100 of which remained so four days after the storm. Overall losses from the storm reached A$1.3&nbsp;million (US$1.1&nbsp;million) with an additional A$1&nbsp;million (US$882,000){{#tag:ref|Monetary values are in 2008 [[Australian dollar|AUD]] and [[United States dollar|USD]]|group=\"nb\"|name=\"Values\"}} in cleanup costs.\n\n==Meteorological history==\n{{storm path|Helen 2007 track.png}}\nAs early as autumn 2007, long-range [[Numerical weather prediction|forecast models]] indicated that a [[La Ni\u00f1a]] would develop by December of that year. In general, this event results in increased [[sea surface temperature]]s near Australia. Following this, a strong [[Madden\u2013Julian oscillation]] phase took shape, leading to the development of [[Tropical Cyclone Melanie (2007)|Tropical Cyclone Melanie]] off the coast of [[Western Australia]] and an [[low-pressure area|area of low pressure]] over the [[Top End]] by 28&nbsp;December. Situated over land, the system initially embedded within a disorganised [[Trough (meteorology)|trough]] and to intensify as it slowly tracked eastward. By 30&nbsp;December, it separated itself from the trough and travelled towards the west. The following day, the interaction between the two systems allowed the low to significantly deepen, attaining a [[barometric pressure]] of 993&nbsp;[[Bar (unit)|mbar]] ([[Pascal (unit)|hPa]]; 29.32&nbsp;[[Inches of Mercury|inHg]]). This strengthening was short-lived as [[wind shear]] over the low increased, displacing [[Atmospheric convection#Concerns regarding severe deep moist convection|convection]] from its centre.<ref name=\"TCR\">{{cite web|work=Darwin Tropical Cyclone Warning Centre|publisher=Australian Bureau of Meteorology|year=2008|accessdate=20 January 2011|title=Tropical Cyclone Helen Tropical Cyclone Report|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/history/pdf/helen.pdf}}</ref>\n\nBy 2&nbsp;January, the weak low moved over the [[Joseph Bonaparte Gulf]] where it slowly developed over the following day.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> Once over water, the [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]] (JTWC) designated the system as Tropical Depression 09S.<ref name=\"JTWCBT\">{{cite web|work=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|publisher=United States Navy|year=2009|accessdate=23 January 2011|title=Tropical Cyclone 09S (Helen) Best Track|url=http://www.usno.navy.mil/NOOC/nmfc-ph/RSS/jtwc/best_tracks/2008/2008s-bsh/bsh102008.txt|format=[[Text file|TXT]]}}</ref> As organisation improved, a mid-level [[subtropical ridge]] over Western Australia pushed the system westward, away from the [[Kimberley (Western Australia)|Kimberley coast]]. Steadily strengthening, the low attained gale-force winds near its centre during the morning of 4&nbsp;January and was subsequently named Helen by the [[Bureau of Meteorology (Australia)|Bureau of Meteorology]]. Shortly thereafter, a strong westerly [[monsoon trough|monsoon flow]] to the north caused Helen to turn eastward, back towards land. Intensification continued up until [[landfall]], by which time Helen had attained Category&nbsp;2 status on the [[Tropical cyclone scales#Australia|Australian tropical cyclone intensity scale]]. [[Maximum sustained wind|Maximum ten-minute sustained wind]]s reached 95&nbsp;km/h (60&nbsp;mph) and the storm's [[barometric pressure]] decreased to 975&nbsp;[[Bar (unit)|mbar]] ([[Pascal (unit)|hPa]]; 28.79&nbsp;[[Inches of Mercury|inHg]]).<ref name=\"TCR\"/> The JTWC assessed Helen to have been slightly weaker, with peak winds estimated at 85&nbsp;km/h (50&nbsp;mph).<ref name=\"JTWCBT\"/>\n\nAround 10:00&nbsp;pm local time on 4&nbsp;January, the centre of Tropical Cyclone Helen made landfall near Channel Point. As it moved ashore, the storm developed an [[Eye (cyclone)|eye]]; however, this feature began breaking apart once overland and the eyewall merged into the system's [[Rainband#Tropical cyclones|feeder bands]]. Roughly 12&nbsp;hours after landfall, Helen weakened to a tropical low before moving over the [[Gulf of Carpentaria]] late on 5&nbsp;January. Due to an increase in forward motion, the system was unable to regenerate sufficient convection to be reclassified a tropical cyclone before making a second landfall along the Cape York Peninsula.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> Once overland again, the remnants of Helen abruptly slowed and were last noted on 7&nbsp;January in the same region.<ref name=\"JTWCBT\"/>\n\n==Preparations==\n[[File:Powerlines down in Alawa following Cyclone Helen.jpg|thumb|right|Trees and power lines downed in Darwin as a result of Cyclone Helen]]\nStarting in late December, widespread rains produced by the precursor to Helen prompted the issuance of flood warnings throughout the Top End region.<ref name=\"TCR\"/><ref name=\"ABC4\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=NT flood warning as low drifts north |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/02/2130427.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxFrYefP?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/02/2130427.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Prior to the arrival of Cyclone Helen on 4&nbsp;January, the Bureau of Meteorology issued [[Tropical cyclone warnings and watches|cyclone warnings]] for areas between the [[Mitchell Plateau]], in Western Australia, to [[Cape Hotham Light|Cape Hotham]] in the Northern Territory. According to local officials, flooding was the greatest concern from the storm rather than wind damage.<ref name=\"ABC1\">{{cite web |author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Top End on alert as cyclone forms |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2131771.htm?site=news |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxC1Rra3?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2131771.htm?site=news |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> The warning area was later condensed to encompass areas from [[Wadeye, Northern Territory|Wadeye]] to Cape Hotham, including Darwin and the [[Tiwi Islands]].<ref name=\"ABC2\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Helen upgraded, shelters open in Darwin |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2132081.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxCeOLkn?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2132081.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> By 6&nbsp;January, warnings were issued for the western coast of the Cape York Peninsula between [[Karumba, Queensland|Karumba]] and [[Weipa, Queensland|Weipa]] as the remnants of Helen were forecast to regain storm intensity.<ref name=\"ABC3\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=6 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Bureau predicts cyclone to hit Cape York |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/06/2132566.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxF5zkc8?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/06/2132566.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn light of Helen's approach in the Top End region, the [[Compass Resources]] mining company suspended construction of a new mine in [[Batchelor, Northern Territory|Batchelor]].<ref name=\"ABC1\"/> Mining at the [[Ranger Uranium Mine]] maintained by [[Energy Resources of Australia]] was also suspended until the storm passed.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rebecca Keenan and Angela Macdonald-Smith|publisher=Bloomberg News|date=4 January 2008|accessdate=23 January 2011|title=Energy Resources Stops Uranium Mining Due to Cyclone (Update2)|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid%3Dnewsarchive%26sid%3DaJc3NJ7_FyIw%26refer%3Daustralia|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxE8LwnD?url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aJc3NJ7_FyIw&refer=australia|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 January 2011}}</ref> The [[George Brown Darwin Botanic Gardens]] and [[Territory Wildlife Park]] were also closed for the duration of the storm.<ref name=\"ABC1\"/> Residents in the [[Aboriginal people#Oceania|Aboriginal community]] of Wadeye were strongly advised to take precautions for the storm.<ref>{{cite web|author=Australian Associated Press |publisher=The North Queensland Register |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone warning for WA and NT |url=http://nqr.farmonline.com.au/news/nationalrural/agribusiness-and-general/general/cyclone-warning-for-wa-and-nt/56915.aspx |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxCRN4xh?url=http://nqr.farmonline.com.au/news/nationalrural/agribusiness-and-general/general/cyclone-warning-for-wa-and-nt/56915.aspx |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Following the issuance of a cyclone warning in Darwin, local shelters were opened to the public.<ref name=\"ABC2\"/> At the [[Darwin International Airport]], all incoming and outgoing flights through [[Jetstar Airways]] were cancelled while [[Tiger Airways]] rescheduled their flights and no changes were made by [[Qantas]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Helen bears down on coast |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2132142.htm?site=news |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxDEDiRO?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2132142.htm?site=news |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Darwin Harbour was mostly shut down as seas became too rough to sail in. Schools and day cares within a {{convert|50|km|mi|abbr=on}} radius of the city were closed on 4&nbsp;January.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tara Ravens |agency=Australian Associated Press |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Helen due to hit NT coast |url=http://news.smh.com.au/national/cyclone-helen-due-to-hit-nt-coast-20080104-1k6n.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxDqDev1?url=http://news.smh.com.au/national/cyclone-helen-due-to-hit-nt-coast-20080104-1k6n.html |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Impact and aftermath==\n[[File:Cyclone Helen 4019.jpg|thumb|left|Power crews clearing trees and fixing downed wires in the wake of Cyclone Helen]]\nThroughout the Top End region, the precursor to Helen resulted in a prolonged period of moderate rains over a relatively large area. These rains caused the Victoria River to swell over its banks and flood nearby areas. On 4&nbsp;January, a car with three people was swept away by the river; two of the passengers managed to escape and swim to shore, but the third person remained trapped. Aerial searches were made later that day for him,<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=4 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Air search for missing NT man |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2131735.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxGP5qiG?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/04/2131735.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> though he was later declared dead.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> After becoming a tropical cyclone, the storm produced additional moderate to heavy rainfall, generally totaling between {{convert|100|and|200|mm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> Between 1 and 6&nbsp;January, a total of {{convert|174.6|mm|in|abbr=on}} of rain fell in Darwin.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Australian Bureau of Meteorology|year=2008|accessdate=23 January 2011|title=2008 Daily Rainfall Summary for Stokes Hill, Northern Territory|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/jsp/ncc/cdio/weatherData/av?p_display_type=dailyDataFile&p_stn_num=014167&p_startYear=2008&statType=Rainfall+of+....&p_nccObsCode=136}}</ref> These rains affected two additional major rivers in the area: the [[Adelaide River|Adelaide]] and [[Katherine River|Katherine]] rivers.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> Near where the storm made landfall, wind gusts up to 120&nbsp;km/h (75&nbsp;mph) were recorded; Darwin recorded a maximum wind gust of {{convert|102|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} as Helen moved by the city.<ref name=\"TCR\"/>\n\nNear Channel Point, the cyclone brought a [[storm surge]] of {{convert|2|to|3|m|ft|abbr=on}}, barely surpassing the highest [[astronomical tide]] in a few areas. In some cases, waves over topped [[sand dune]]s but no damage took place. Roughly 10-15% of trees in open areas were snapped or uprooted by high winds. Only two structures sustained direct wind damage while several others were struck by downed trees. Damage was more widespread in Darwin where roughly 15,000 homes, 60% of the city's residences, were left without power. Approximately 1,500 trees were downed in the city, falling on roads, homes and power lines. In the days following the storm's passage, the Adelaide and Katherine rivers continued to rise, of which the former exceeded minor flood levels.<ref name=\"TCR\"/> In the harbour, seven vessels washed ashore, each sustaining minor damage.<ref name=\"ABC6\"/> Losses caused by the storm was placed at A$1.3&nbsp;million (US$1.1&nbsp;million).{{#tag:ref||name=\"Values\"|group=\"nb\"}}<ref name=\"ABC5\">{{cite web|author=Margie Smithurst |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=29 February 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Trees |url=http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/nt/content/2006/s2176883.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxKQJ7Zf?url=http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/nt/content/2006/s2176883.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe day after Helen passed through, cleanup efforts began as power crews had to remove downed trees before fixing power lines.<ref>{{cite web|author=Australian Associated Press |publisher=News.au |date=5 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Helen still a threat |url=http://www.news.com.au/cyclone-helen-still-a-threat/story-e6frfkp9-1111115252958 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxK9HvWf?url=http://www.news.com.au/cyclone-helen-still-a-threat/story-e6frfkp9-1111115252958 |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> The main power lines in the city were restored within 24&nbsp;hours and rural areas were stated to have their power back within a day or two.<ref>{{cite web |author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=6 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Power restored to Darwin homes after cyclone |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/06/2132504.htm?section=australia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxKyPANS?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/06/2132504.htm?section=australia |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Two days after the storm, 500 homes remained without electricity and frustrated residents were further angered after discovering that the Power and Water agency was in control of tree removal and not emergency services. With the power company in charge of clearing downed trees, they stated that their crews would only be dealing with cases involved power lines. Residents with trees in their yards or even on their homes were told to contact private contractors to remove them.<ref name=\"ABC6\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=7 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Power and Water take strong stance over tree-clearing |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/07/2132968.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxLkLJnb?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/07/2132968.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> By 9&nbsp;January, more than 100 homes were still without power in northern Darwin, resulting in angry outcries from those still left in the dark.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ben Langford |newspaper=Northern Territory News |date=9 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Power delay anger |url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2008/01/09/3049_ntnews.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxLHVvnH?url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2008/01/09/3049_ntnews.html |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Cleanup efforts dragged on for more than two months as debris was still present in Darwin in March.<ref name=\"ABC5\"/> Removal of tree stumps took through at least mid-April as the cost to remove downed trees exceeded A$1&nbsp;million (US$882,000).{{#tag:ref||name=\"Values\"|group=\"nb\"}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=18 April 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2011 |title=Cyclone Helen clean-up bill hits $1m |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/04/18/2221033.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vxKnxS8M?url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/04/18/2221033.htm |archivedate=January 23, 2011 }}</ref> Due to the damage wrought by Helen, its name was [[Tropical cyclone naming#Retirement|retired]] following its usage. However, it was not replaced by any particular name as a new naming scheme was implemented the following season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/about/names.shtml|publisher=Bureau of Meteorology|year=2010|title=Tropical Cyclone Names}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season]]\n*[[Timeline of the 2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season]]\n*[[Cyclone Gretel]]&nbsp;\u2013 The last storm to bring gale-force winds to [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] prior to Helen\n*[[Cyclone Carlos (2011)|Cyclone Carlos]]&nbsp;\u2013 The next cyclone to hit Darwin, bringing record rainfall to the city.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cyclone Helen}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070421094952/http://www.wmo.int/index-en.html World Meteorological Organization]\n* [http://www.bom.gov.au/weather/cyclone/ Australian Bureau of Meteorology]\n* [http://www.usno.navy.mil/JTWC Joint Typhoon Warning Center]\n\n{{2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season buttons}}\n{{Retired Australian cyclones}}\n{{Category 2 Australian region tropical cyclones}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Helen (2008)}}\n[[Category:2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season|2007\u201308 Australian region cyclone season]]\n[[Category:Category 2 Australian region cyclones]]\n[[Category:1990\u201391 Australian region cyclone season]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCyclone Gretel(link changed to1984\u201385 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical_Cyclone_Gretel) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclone_Helen_(2008)"}
